<h6 class="kicker"></h6>
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">ICAHN TAKES AIM AT FAMILY DOLLAR <span class="divider">&nbsp;|&nbsp;</span></span><!-- end .title --> The activist investor Carl C. Icahn, who has a long record of aggressively lobbying corporate boards and management, has turned his attention to Family Dollar Stores, the discount retailer in which he holds a 9.39 percent stake, <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/06/19/icahn-urges-family-dollar-to-sell-itself">DealBookâs William Alden writes</a></b>. In a letter to Howard R. Levine, Family Dollarâs chief executive, Mr. Icahn urged the company to self itself âimmediately.â He also demanded that three of his representatives be added to Family Dollarâs board. If the company does not cooperate, Mr. Icahn said he plans to <b>go directly to shareholders</b> with an effort to throw out the entire board.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><b>The letter was the first public indication</b> of Mr. Icahnâs plans for his new investment in Family Dollar, which he disclosed earlier this month. For its part, Family Dollar has fortified its defenses, adopting a one-year shareholder rights plan, known as a poison pill. In his letter, Mr. Icahn noted the companyâs <b>disappointing financial results</b> and said that âconsolidationâ in the companyâs industry was âinevitable.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Activist behavior like Mr. Icahnâs has recently drawn criticism from within the hedge fund industry, <b><a href=" //online.wsj.com/articles/valueacts-ubben-has-a-new-target-his-hedge-fund-peers-1403219008?mod=WSJ_hp_LEFTWhatsNewsCollection">The Wall Street Journal writes</a></b>. Jeffrey Ubben, the founder of the hedge fund ValueAct Capital Management, has expressed fear that recent behavior by some of his peers could give activism a bad reputation. In particular, Mr. Ubben, who calls himself a friendly activist, called out Mr. Icahn, saying some of his recent moves, including trying to persuade eBay to spin off PayPal, have not been constructive. </p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">LOOKING AHEAD AFTER ARGENTINA RULING <span class="divider">&nbsp;|&nbsp;</span></span><!-- end .title --> With its ruling on Argentina this week, the United States Supreme Court âturned the world of sovereign debt restructuring on its head,â <b><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/06/20/business/economy/ruling-on-argentina-gives-investors-an-upper-hand.html">Floyd Norris writes in the High &#038; Low Finance column</a></b>. âIn so doing, the court most likely damaged the status of New York as the worldâs financial capital. It made it far less likely that genuinely troubled countries will be able to restructure their debts. And it <b>increased the power of investors</b>â to prevent needed restructurings.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8220;<b>The hand of holdouts has been strengthened immensely</b>. Under the ruling by the United States Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit, holdouts cannot fare any worse than those who agree to a restructuring â and they can do much better,â he writes. Still, &#8220;<b>it is hard to muster much sympathy for Argentina</b>, which chose to cram down a brutal restructuring plan years after defaulting, when it reasonably could have been more generous. But this decision is likely to hurt countries whose financial problems are much more serious.â </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Now that Argentina has lost its appeal against the hedge fund Elliott Management, it has two choices: negotiate a settlement with Elliott or default on its current debts. So what now? <b><a href="//www.bloombergview.com/articles/2014-06-19/what-will-argentina-do-with-its-vultures">Matt Levine of Bloomberg View writes</a></b>: âElliottâs leverage over Argentina is that it can force Argentina to default on its bonds, which would be a big setback in its efforts to rejoin the world capital markets. But thatâs a one-time event: <b>Once it happens, Elliottâs leverage evaporates</b>. Once Argentina defaults, itâs defaulted; Elliott canât make it default any more.â So, he adds, âa calmer negotiation, a bit more removed from the shadow of default, might be better for both sides.â</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">ALSTOM BIDDING HEATS UP <span class="divider">&nbsp;|&nbsp;</span></span><!-- end .title --> Siemens of Germany and Mitsubishi Heavy of Japan said on Friday that they were <b>raising the cash component of their offer for Alstom</b>, the French industrial company at the center of their takeover battle with General Electric, in a last-ditch effort to swing the contest their way, <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/06/20/in-last-ditch-effort-duo-raises-offer-in-bid-for-alstom">David Jolly writes in DealBook</a></b>. Their new proposal increases the cash component of their offer by 1.2 billion euros to â¬8.2 billion euros, or $11.2 billion, valuing Alstomâs energy business at â¬14.6 billion, â¬400 million more than previously proposed.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The two companies announced their new offer just one day after G.E. <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/06/19/g-e-alters-its-alstom-bid-in-effort-to-win-french-support">revised its own $13.5 billion bid</a></b> for Alstomâs energy business as both bidding camps sought to ease the concerns of President FranÃ§ois Hollandeâs government. Instead of a straightforward takeover of Alstomâs energy assets, G.E. is now proposing a structure that keeps some of those assets under an Alstom roof. G.E. did not change the financial valuation of the $13.5 billion deal, but it is now <b>proposing to create two joint ventures with Alstom</b>: one in the power grid business and another in renewable energy. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In any case, <b>the maneuvering appears to be entering its final stages</b>. G.E.âs chief executive, Jeffrey R. Immelt, is in Paris for talks on Friday with Mr. Hollande, and Alstomâs board faces a Monday deadline on deciding whether to accept the G.E. offer. Alstom said in a statement that its board would meet no later than Monday to review the two offers but that it planned no further communications on the process</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">ON THE AGENDA <span class="divider">&nbsp;|&nbsp;</span></span><!-- end .title --> The Atlanta Fed <b>business inflation expectations survey</b> is out at 10 a.m. Saturday is the <b>first official day of summer</b>. <b>Mary Jo White</b>, the chairwoman of the Securities and Exchange Commission, speaks to the Economic Club of New York at 12:15 p.m.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><b>World Cup watch</b>: <b>Italy vs. Costa Rica</b> at 12 p.m. <b>Switzerland vs. France</b> at 3 p.m. <b>Honduras vs. Ecuador</b> at 6 p.m.</p>
</div>
